39:18.613 --> 39:19.954
Recent stuff?

39:19.974 --> 39:21.797
Recent stuff.

39:21.817 --> 39:27.024
And how do you determine... I mean, I don't want to give away my detecting methods.

39:27.044 --> 39:27.745
Oh, I quite agree.

39:27.765 --> 39:33.233
Yeah, you know, but I mean, I use every available source that I have at my fingertips.

39:34.833 --> 39:36.615
Can you give me some examples of things?

39:36.635 --> 39:39.397
I use copyright records.

39:41.839 --> 39:43.381
Can you give me some examples of writers?

39:44.081 --> 39:47.925
Well, I'd rather not mention their names, you know.

39:48.345 --> 39:54.691
There's only one or two that I know that have, you know, admitted.

39:54.751 --> 39:58.755
One is Lawrence Block, who's a mystery writer.

39:59.755 --> 40:03.559
Donald Westlake, he's a mystery writer.

40:03.619 --> 40:04.840
He's admitted, you know.

40:05.157 --> 40:07.240
This is stuff they wrote for money.

40:07.280 --> 40:10.684
How do you find this stuff?

40:10.744 --> 40:15.871
I don't mean the actual records.

40:16.812 --> 40:19.976
How do you find the original material?

40:21.678 --> 40:32.953
Being a book collector at the same time, I always was interested in the stuff that falls in between the cracks that publishers don't make and are known.

40:33.490 --> 40:36.013
paperback books for a long, long time.

40:36.674 --> 40:38.817
Never got into, you know, books in print.

40:39.778 --> 40:40.159
Never.

40:40.819 --> 40:43.863
And they fell in between the cracks.

40:43.964 --> 40:58.562
Now, you know, from just working in AAS, you know, trying to figure out stuff that, you know, publishers published a hundred years ago, you know, this stuff just disappeared because no record was kept.

40:59.023 --> 41:02.147
And, you know, at one time, I was collecting...

41:02.380 --> 41:08.928
the paperback books of one publisher who had been in business since 1963 to 1973.

41:09.309 --> 41:17.879
